\subsection{Wall-Clock Speed Analysis}
\label{ssec:throughput}
We evaluate the wall-clock performance of the SDAR-8B model on an industrial inference engine powered by an NVIDIA H200 GPU. Figure~\ref{fig:tgs_comparison} reports the Tokens Generated Per Second (TGS) across varying block sizes ($B$) and batch sizes, comparing our dynamic and static strategies against the standard AR baseline.
\paragraph{Latency-Sensitive Regime (Small Batch).}
The primary advantage of \textsc{SDAR} is observed in the latency-sensitive regime (batch sizes $1 \sim 32$), which corresponds to real-time interactive applications. In this memory-bound setting, standard AR is limited by memory bandwidth due to repeated weight loading for single-token generation. \textsc{SDAR} mitigates this by generating multiple tokens per forward pass, significantly improving memory efficiency.
As shown in Figure~\ref{fig:tgs_comparison}, \textsc{SDAR} consistently outperforms AR at lower batch sizes. Notably, with a large block size of $B=64$ and a batch size of 4, Dynamic \textsc{SDAR} achieves a $2.3\times$ speedup over the AR baseline.
\paragraph{Throughput-Bound Regime (Large Batch).}
Our optimized inference engine achieves impressive peak throughputs (e.g., over 6,000 TGS at high concurrency), confirming the efficiency of the underlying implementation. However, as the batch size increases ($>32$), the system transitions from a memory-bound to a compute-bound regime.
Since \textsc{SDAR} incurs higher arithmetic intensity (processing $B$ candidates per step) compared to AR, the GPU's compute capacity becomes the bottleneck at high concurrency. Consequently, the relative speedup diminishes, and AR eventually surpasses \textsc{SDAR} in pure throughput as the batch size scales towards 128.
\section{Study IV: Local Non-Causal Modeling Capabilities}
\label{sec:study4}
Standard AR models are constrained by strict left-to-right causality. \textsc{SDAR} mitigates this via blockwise diffusion, introducing a \textbf{local non-causal} property where tokens within a block attend bidirectionally.
By adapting a science-specialized backbone (Qwen3-30B-A3B-Sci), we isolate the impact of this relaxation on structured domains and analyze its synergy with test-time scaling.
\subsection{Structured and General Capabilities}
\label{ssec:science_domain}
Scientific data (e.g., molecular graphs) often involves non-linear dependencies challenging token-level causal masking.
We posit \textsc{SDAR}'s locally bidirectional design offers a superior inductive bias for these structures.
Table~\ref{tab:combined_results_wide} reports performance across 10 benchmarks.
\paragraph{Local bidirectionality captures structural dependencies.}
\textsc{SDAR} shows distinct advantages in structure-rich tasks, achieving significant gains on {ChemBench (+12.3)} and the expert-level {GPQA-diamond (+5.5)}.
We attribute this to the \textbf{relaxation of token-level causality}: intra-block bidirectional attention allows the model to capture local topology (e.g., molecular bonds) without the constraints of sequential generation order.
\paragraph{Global sequential logic is preserved.}
Crucially, this structural enhancement does not compromise general reasoning. As shown in Table~\ref{tab:combined_results_wide} (right), \textsc{SDAR} remains strong on logic-heavy benchmarks (MMLU-Pro, AIME) and outperforms AR on complex tasks like LiveMathBench-Hard (+5.3) and LiveCodeBench (+5.1). This indicates that modifying the local attention mechanism enhances structural modeling without disrupting the global chain-of-thought logic learned in pretraining.
\subsection{Diversity and Test-Time Scaling}
\label{ssec:test_time_scaling}
We further examine the interaction between diffusion-based stochasticity and test-time scaling (Majority Voting and Pass@k) in Table~\ref{tab:ar_vs_sdar_delta_transposed_subset}.
\paragraph{Diffusion noise maximizes ensemble efficiency.}
\textsc{SDAR} demonstrates exceptional synergy with scaling strategies. While single-sample performance rivals AR, ensemble inference yields outsized gains: {+19.3 on AIME25} and {+15.7 on LiveMathBench-hard}.
Similarly, Pass@32 metrics reach 93.3 on AIME24.
These results suggest that the non-causal generation process produces a greater diversity of valid reasoning paths. Consequently, \textsc{SDAR} serves as a highly effective generator for compute-intensive ("System 2") inference, converting test-time compute into accuracy more efficiently than standard AR sampling.

